### Best Under $10,000 — The Premium Tier

**Two paths exist here, depending on origin preference:**

**Natural path:** A 1ct G-VS1 with an excellent quality pavé or halo setting, or a 1.5ct natural in the $6,000–$9,000 range with GIA Excellent cut. The 1.5ct natural delivers 7.3mm face-up for roughly $6,500–$8,000 in G-VS2 with Excellent cut — check Blue Nile's 1.5ct section, filtering GIA Excellent, G color, VS2, and applying the proportion numbers manually.

**Lab path:** The IGI 2ct D-VVS1 at $2,810 (ID [28629934](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28629934?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)) leaves $7,190 budget for an exceptional setting — a platinum 6-prong solitaire ($1,200–$1,800), quality pavé band ($1,500–$2,500), or a three-stone design with lab flanking stones. The total ring at $4,000–$5,300 all-in is an 8.1mm D-VVS1 in a premium setting. Nothing in the natural under-$10,000 tier touches this combination of size and grade specification.

**Buyer's Triangle at $10K:** Natural buyers should apply the Triangle normally (GIA EX, G, VS2). Lab buyers should spend at the 2ct D-VVS1 and redirect budget to setting quality.

