## Common Overpaying Traps — Mistakes That Cost $3,000–$30,000

**Trap 1 — The Colorless Premium:** Upgrading from G to D at 1ct costs $560. At 2ct it costs $10,000. At 3ct it costs $24,150. The visual difference is imperceptible in normal lighting at any of these sizes. G is face-up white. Stay at G.

**Trap 2 — The Invisible Clarity Tax:** Upgrading from VS2 to VVS1 at 1ct costs $420. At 2ct it costs $10,120. At 3ct the gap is even larger. VVS1 and VS2 are equally invisible to the naked eye in round brilliants. Stay at VS2.

**Trap 3 — The VVS Upgrade Treadmill:** Some buyers start at VS2, then justify a one-step upgrade to VS1, then VVS2, then VVS1. Each step "seems small." The cumulative cost from VS2 to VVS1 is $2,000–$14,880 depending on carat. Decide once and stay there.

**Trap 4 — Asymmetric brand premium:** "Astor by Blue Nile" designates top-performing stones using their proprietary Light Performance system. These stones carry 10–20% price premiums over standard GIA Excellent. Whether that premium is justified depends on the individual stone's proportions — a standard GIA Excellent with ideal proportions performs as well as any Astor stone. Verify proportions before paying the Astor premium.

**Trap 5 — The Setting Budget Neglect:** Buyers sometimes spend their entire budget on the stone and select a low-quality setting to stay in budget. A $4,000 stone in a $150 setting is a worse ring than a $3,500 stone in a $500 setting. Allocate at minimum 10–15% of total ring budget to the setting.

## Metal Choice: The Correct Answer at Each Budget

**Under $5,000:** 14k white gold. Identical visual appearance to platinum for any observer; $300–$600 cheaper than the equivalent setting in platinum. 14k wears slightly softer than platinum — budget an annual rhodium replating ($40–$80) every 12–18 months.

**$5,000–$20,000:** 18k white gold or platinum. At this budget, the additional cost of platinum ($200–$500 more than 18k WG) is proportionally small and offers genuine durability benefits — platinum is more resistant to scratches and does not require rhodium replating.

**$20,000+:** Platinum is the correct metal. At this investment level, the durability, density, and lifetime maintenance advantage of platinum over gold is fully justified. Platinum's natural white color also ensures the stone appears at maximum brilliance over decades of wear without periodic replating.

