## Frequently Asked Questions

### What is the best round diamond for an engagement ring?

The best round diamond is defined by The Buyer's Triangle: GIA Excellent cut with verified proportions (table 54–57%, depth 59–62.3%), G color, VS2 clarity. At 1ct, that's the G-VS2 at $3,230. At 2ct, it's the G-VS2 at $16,490. The formula is consistent across all carat weights — only the price changes.

### What size round diamond is best for an engagement ring?

The most popular engagement ring size in the US is 1ct (6.5mm). This is the size most buyers picture when they imagine an engagement ring. At 2ct (8.1mm), the stone reads as premium and impressive. Under 0.90ct, the stone reads as fashion jewelry rather than a traditional engagement ring. The correct size depends on budget, hand size, and personal preference.

### What is the best setting for a round cut diamond?

A 4-prong or 6-prong solitaire. It maximizes light entry, provides secure prong placement, and is proportionally balanced at every carat weight. Pavé band solitaires add band detail without competing with the center. Halos add visual size. Three-stone settings add drama. All of these can be excellent — solitaire is the safest and most versatile choice.

### Is GIA certification necessary for the best round diamond?

Yes, for natural diamonds. GIA certification ensures accurate grading and long-term resale documentation. An IGI-graded natural diamond may be 1–2 color grades and 1 clarity grade more generous than GIA — a "G-VS2 IGI natural" may be an H-SI1 on GIA standards. For lab diamonds, IGI and GCAL are both acceptable.

### What color is best for a round cut diamond engagement ring?

G color in white gold or platinum. G is the top of the "Near Colorless" range and appears face-up white without the D–F premium. In yellow or rose gold, H color is appropriate — the warm metal makes H's faint warmth read as harmonious. Never go below H for white gold; never go below G for platinum settings.

### What clarity is best for a round diamond ring?

VS2 is the correct clarity floor. At 1ct, VS2 round brilliants are eye-clean in 90%+ of cases. At 2ct, VS2 is borderline — always watch HD video to confirm. VVS and above are invisible improvements carrying significant premiums. VS1 is one unnecessary step above VS2; VVS is two. SI1 requires individual video verification but can be eye-clean in well-positioned inclusions.

### Should I buy a natural or lab-grown diamond for an engagement ring?

Buy natural if: the social and sentimental value of natural origin matters to you, if resale value is a priority, or if your budget allows 1ct+ natural. Buy lab if: you want maximum size per dollar, origin doesn't matter, and resale is not a priority. The IGI 2ct D-VVS1 lab at $2,810 vs natural 1ct G-VS2 at $3,230 presents a meaningful trade-off that only your priorities can resolve.

### How do I know if I'm overpaying for a diamond ring?

You're overpaying if: the stone is above H color in white gold (paying for invisible color), above VS1 clarity (paying for invisible clarity), not GIA Excellent cut (paying for visible quality degradation), or if the stone is a fancy brand designation (Astor, Ideal) without proportion verification confirming the premium is warranted. Apply The Buyer's Triangle and the five proportion numbers — overpaying leaves a clear data trail.

### How much should I spend on an engagement ring?

The "three months' salary" guideline is marketing invented by De Beers in the 1930s. Spend what you can afford without financial stress. At every price point from $2,000 to $50,000, there is a correct, analytically defensible ring choice. The $3,230 1ct G-VS2 GIA Excellent on Blue Nile is one of the best-value large purchases in any category. The quality does not require a salary multiple.

### What is the best brand for a round diamond engagement ring?

Blue Nile is the correct platform for round diamond engagement ring purchases. Their GIA Excellent 1ct+ inventory is the deepest in the industry, HD video is available for every stone, prices are public and competitive, and their return policy is 30 days with free return shipping. For custom settings or unusual sizes, James Allen is a strong alternative. Tiffany charges a 40–80% brand premium that buys a box, not a better stone.

### How long does it take to receive a Blue Nile engagement ring?

A standard solitaire with an in-stock stone typically ships within 3–5 business days and arrives in 7–14 business days with FedEx delivery. Custom settings with special sizing or engraving add 5–10 business days. Blue Nile provides real-time tracking and insures the shipment at full retail value.

### Is rose gold appropriate for a round diamond engagement ring?

Yes, with the correct stone selection. Rose gold requires H color or warmer for the center stone — the warm copper tones in rose gold make G color look slightly cool or neutral, while H color reads as intentionally warm and harmonious. Rose gold settings currently trend upward in popularity and are fully appropriate for any round brilliant.

